    title: "The Active Learning Loop: Implementation Details",
    content: "Implementing the active learning loop requires connecting four components: the current model, the unlabeled data pool, the selection strategy, and the annotation pipeline. The implementation follows a clean separation of concerns.\n\nThe model component runs inference on the unlabeled pool and produces confidence scores. For PyTorch models, this involves setting the model to eval mode, iterating over the unlabeled data with a DataLoader, computing softmax probabilities, and collecting confidence scores alongside data identifiers.\n\nThe selection component sorts samples by uncertainty and selects the top-K most uncertain. The K value depends on the labeling budget for this iteration. Selecting too few (K=10) wastes the annotators' time on task overhead. Selecting too many (K=10000) may include some easy samples that do not improve the model, but provides more diversity.\n\nThe annotation component creates tasks in CVAT or Labelbox, waits for completion, and downloads the results. This step involves human annotators and is typically the slowest part of the loop, taking hours or days depending on annotation complexity and team size.\n\nThe retraining component adds the new labels to the training set and retrains the model. A critical implementation detail is that retraining should start from the previous model weights, not from scratch. Fine-tuning from the previous checkpoint is computationally cheaper and leverages the knowledge already acquired. However, periodic full retraining prevents the model from overfitting to the selection bias of the active learning strategy.\n\nThe DataLoader for newly labeled data, referenced in the code as new_annotations_loader, wraps the freshly annotated dataset for integration into the training pipeline. In the simplest implementation, new annotations are appended to the existing training dataset and the model is retrained on the full combined set. More sophisticated approaches weight recent annotations more heavily to prioritize new knowledge.\n\nThe loop continues until a stopping criterion is met. The most common criteria are: the model accuracy on a held-out test set reaches the target threshold, the labeling budget is exhausted, or the model performance plateaus after several iterations, indicating diminishing returns from additional labels.",
