    title: "Domain Adaptation and Active Learning for Drone Deployments",
    content: "Domain adaptation is a critical challenge for drone AI systems. A model trained on data from one geographic region, season, or weather condition may perform poorly when deployed in a different domain. Active learning directly addresses this challenge by identifying samples from the new domain where the model is uncertain.\n\nConsider a fire detection model trained on images from Mediterranean forests being deployed to monitor boreal forests in Canada. The vegetation types, terrain characteristics, and smoke patterns differ significantly. Running the model on unlabeled boreal forest images and selecting the least confident predictions identifies exactly the images that represent the domain gap, the visual characteristics the model has not learned.\n\nLabeling these domain-specific uncertain samples and retraining produces a model adapted to the new domain with far fewer labels than would be required to train from scratch. This is domain adaptation through active learning: the selection strategy naturally targets the domain shift.\n\nDiversity sampling complements confidence-based selection for domain adaptation. Pure confidence-based selection might repeatedly select similar images, like images of a specific unfamiliar tree species, creating redundancy. Diversity sampling ensures the selected batch covers the breadth of the new domain by clustering the uncertain samples and selecting from different clusters.\n\nProduction integration means the active learning loop runs continuously. As drones capture new data during operations, the inference pipeline flags low-confidence detections. These flagged images accumulate in a review queue. Periodically, a batch is sent for annotation and the model is retrained. This creates a continuously improving system that adapts to seasonal changes, new deployment regions, and evolving conditions.\n\nThe automation of sample selection and labeling requests is the key to production integration. Manual review of model confidence scores is feasible for research but not for operational systems processing thousands of images daily. Automated pipelines trigger annotation tasks when the accumulated uncertain sample count exceeds a threshold, maintaining the active learning loop without manual intervention.",
